Here's how to do it using `Window` lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**1. Create a custom `Window` subclass:**

```csharp
// AppWindow.cs
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        if (Page is AppShell shell
            && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
        {
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", note.ViewModel.DraftText);
        }
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        if (Page is AppShell shell
            && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
        {
            note.ViewModel.DraftText =
                Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
        }
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        if (Page is AppShell shell
            && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage note)
        {
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", note.ViewModel.DraftText);
        }
    }
}
```

**2. Return it from `App.CreateWindow`:**

```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    => new AppWindow(new AppShell());
```

**Key points:**

- **`OnStopped`** — fires when the app is fully backgrounded; save here.
- **`OnResumed`** — fires when returning from background; restore here.
- **`OnDestroying`** — also save here because Android's back button can skip `Stopped` and go straight to `Destroying`.
- **`Resumed` does NOT fire on first launch** — the initial sequence is `Created → Activated`. Load any persisted draft in your page's `OnAppearing` or constructor for the cold-start case.
- **Keep handlers fast** (<1–2 s) — `Preferences` is ideal for small values like draft text. Avoid database writes or network calls.
